            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers standing on a Mission District rooftop in late 1998, a beer cold in his hand. Below, the city throbbed with dot-com mania, a frantic energy he didn\u2019t quite understand. While others talked of virtual capital, he just watched the physical grid of lights, the headlights on 101, the solid, tangible structures. A wave of profound calm hit him. He wasn\u2019t here for the hype; he was here for the hardware. That moment cemented a path of practicality that would see him through the coming bust.\n\n2.\nThe memory is sun-drenched: Chloe, maybe six years old, finally pushing off on her two-wheeler without training wheels on JFK Drive. For a split second, his heart was in his throat, his hand hovering behind her seat. But then she was off, pedaling furiously, a small, determined figure against the backdrop of the de Young. The swell of pride was overwhelming. It was the first true glimpse of her independence, and it became the quiet joy that has fueled him ever since, a moment from around 2008.\n\n3.\nThe day he moved into his NoPa apartment, a decade ago, was gray and silent. After assembling his bed frame\u2014a familiar, mechanical comfort\u2014he sat on the floor and stared out the window. It wasn\u2019t bitterness he felt, but the hollow ache of a shared life ending. In that profound quiet, he made a vow to be Chloe\u2019s unwavering foundation. The grief forged his stability, transforming him from a partner in a family to its sole, reliable anchor.\n\n4.\nIt was 2001, and the office was a graveyard of empty Aeron chairs. While the company\u2019s software teams were being gutted, Mark was in the workshop, methodically fixing a critical fabrication machine that had failed. His boss, pale with stress, just watched. When Mark finished and the machine whirred back to life, the silent nod of approval he received was more valuable than any stock option. It taught him that in a city of dreams, competence was real currency.\n\n5.\nJust last spring, on a routine run through the Panhandle as the fog began to burn off. He wasn\u2019t thinking of work or his to-do list, just the rhythm of his feet on the path and the scent of eucalyptus. He stopped, catching his breath, and felt a profound sense of peace settle over him. This wasn't the city he had moved to; it was the home he had built, one steady day at a time. The feeling wasn't triumph, but a quiet, earned belonging."
